[I apologize for the almost word-for-word repetition but the first report mentioned depositing a stone as well as a diagnosis of appendicitis. This "stone" may be real or a local aphorism for an embarrassing surgical mistake.

With gastroenteric anthrax the abdomen fills with a hemorrhagic fluid containing the anthrax toxins. Efficient and successful treatment consists of antibiotic treatment and draining this fluid, which may have to be repeated a few times. Antibiotic treatment on its own may kill the pathogen, usually quickly, but does nothing to neutralise these toxins. The patient cannot recover until this fluid is gone and not reappearing.

To find Nineveh in northern Iraq, go to: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ninevehm. And with thanks to Mahmoud. - Mod.MHJ

